    <h2>The Aesthetic of Systems</h2>
    <p>
      Historically, art sought to replicate nature. Today, a significant subset of digital artists seek to replicate, romanticize, or distort the systems we exist within. The <strong>Digital Underground</strong> aesthetic embraces:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Glitch Art:</strong> Finding beauty in the corruption of data. The unintended visual artifacts of failing hardware or mangled compression algorithms.</li>
      <li><strong>Brutalismo de Código (Code Brutalism):</strong> Raw, unpolished, structural web and graphic design. Heavy monospace fonts, stark borders, and absolute minimalism.</li>
      <li><strong>Retro-Hardware & Technical Vaporwave:</strong> Aesthetics pulling from 70s and 80s computing, magnetic tapes, amber terminals, but merged with modern networking concepts.</li>
      <li><strong>Cyber-Gothic:</strong> A darker, melancholic variation focusing on the isolation of the developer and the vastness of the cyberspace—a "data graveyard" aesthetic.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why We Curate This Culture</h2>
    <p>
      At CrakingWall, we recognize that to a developer or digital creator, a screen isn't just a medium—it's an environment. General wallpaper sites offer sunsets and sports cars. We believe the tech community deserves a gallery that speaks directly to their daily experience. 
    </p>
    <p>
      By curating premium <em>tech culture wallpapers</em>, we are archiving a very specific moment in digital art history. We look at the beauty of server racks, the poetry of a well-formatted command line, and the haunting solitude of a digital megacity.
    </p>

    <h2>The Value of Curation</h2>
    <p>
